But that's just what I think! Feel free to comment whether you agree, disagree, or have a lot of thoughts about video-based social media. It's only going to grow as Gen Z gets older and technology advances. Anyways, thanks for coming to my Ted Talk.

I also see a lack of appeal for users to make the switch (or use both). Byte doesn't have the audience, clout, or creative tools necessary to make the content that is successful on a variety of platforms. It really just feels like someone was trying to relive Vine's peak in 2013.
I found it uncomfortable(?) to watch such short content after adjusting to the lengths of TikToks. I wanted longer better-developed content, not shorter content aimed to fit in a short time frame.

Byte is trying soooooooooooooo hard to be Vine 2.0. There's not really a point in bringing back an app that was only good because of its romanticized image. Also, a lot of users have been accustomed to *slightly* longer content.

I think 6 seconds was a great starting point for Vine. It gave the app it's defining feature. But ultimately short content didn't match with the shift in culture. This is also why I think @byte_app won't see the same success TikTok is.

Additionally, TikTok was created with content creation in mind. The number of filters, effects, and music options make it a great place to start creating user-generated video content. Users also aren't pressed to fit an idea into 6 seconds. TikTok caps their time limit at 1min.

TikTok fed off its original success as https://t.co/BlSLVvLH1A. But the app continues to grow because of the trends it creates. TikTok has created its own ecosystem of ideas that spread to other social platforms. Vine never really did that.

Vine (#RIPVine) died for a variety of reasons, namely lack of funding and not keeping up with other social platforms that incorporated video (hello IG). Now that @tiktok_us is growing, a lot of people are quick to say that it's the new Vine. Heres why it's not-

That being said, Vine had its moment. However, no one really saw the GOOD content until after it was deleted. It was never the app that was great, it was the content that surfaced months later. We only thought Vine was good because pop culture romanticized it.

Vine's demographic was younger. While this didn't mean that ALL content was bad, it meant that a lot of it mediocre at best (i.e. Lele Pons *barf*). A LOT of the content made was by high schoolers sharing weird things their friends did- which TBH, wasn't really funny.

Vine was released during my sophomore year of HS. It was revolutionary as it was one of the first video-based social media platforms. Vine was designed to share short life moments but the culture quickly shifted to content creation once it became popular.
With some encouragement from @MrConnorGrant I'm here to share my ~lukewarm~ take on why Vine was never cool, @tiktok_us is NOT the new Vine, and @byte_app  will flop. 🧵
